body:
I have recently come to the decision that I want to leave my mothers place after speaking with a coworker that plans to leave his place in a few months. The problem is that my mom would be quite destitute if I do so since she relies on my income at the moment.

&#x200B;

Im using a new account for this one because I can't remember the login credentials and didn't feel like going through the process of making a new one.

&#x200B;

Last week, at a happy hour company outing, I spoke with another co worker of mine about wanting to move out of my moms place and he mentioned how he was trying to do the same. He seems really cool and even gave a relatively reasonable time frame of a few months. I asked specifically if 3 months was alright instead and he said that it was absolutely fine. This got me really revved up about finally moving out. I've been staying back because my mom would not be able to support herself on her own. However, I don't think I want to pass up this opportunity.

&#x200B;

I don't like living with my mom. I find her to be controlling and manipulative based on the things she's said to me in the past. I am usually afraid to say whats on my mind when it comes to money because I feel like what I say will be taken the wrong way and that I'm accusing her of not trying hard enough. To some degree, I think that may be true. I have offered to pay for her to take the esthetician test to get her license, but she has never followed up or studied for it. Therapists in the past have mentioned that my mom is the prime reason for my stress.

&#x200B;

Whenever I say something back, she usually is accusatory and calls me names or says I treat her poorly because I don't respond back with much emotion, essentially. This is due with the suggestion that she may be a narcissist, so I adopted a method of dealing with her called "grey walling" or being a "grey rock." Which is essentially just keeping dialogue to a bare minimum and not opening conversation. "how are you?" "fine, thanks" and then finishing the conversation. I don't believe this has worked because she can talk 45 minutes about her distress and hark back to years when she wants to use my dad as an example of how I'm shitty because I'm like my dad.

&#x200B;

I've given her essentially $10,000 since I started my job last year to catch up on rent. And now she wanted me to help with the credit card debt, of which is mostly mine to help in the past few years to help us keep the apartment. I don't really want to give her more money but she's going to ask for more for furniture and for the credit card debt in the upcoming 6 months if I stay.

&#x200B;

WIBTA if I tell my mom I'm going to leave in 3 months anyway after everything she's told me as to how that would leave her high and dry since she relies on my income? I'm miserable living here.

